===Alternative forms===
* [[to-day]] {{qualifier|archaic}}

===Etymology===
Via {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|sc=unicode|todæge|tōdæge|lang=ang}}, {{term||tō dæge||on [the] day|lang=ang}}, made from {{term||tō||at, on|lang=ang}} + {{term||dæge|lang=ang}}, the dative of {{term|dæg|sc=unicode|lang=ang||day}}.
* The first component [''to-''] is from {{etyl|enm|-}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|tō||towards, for the purpose of|lang=ang}}, from West Germanic {{recons|to}}, from {{proto|ine-pro|do-|to, toward, upward}}.
* The second component [''-day''] is from {{etyl|enm|-}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|dæg|lang=ang|sc=unicode}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|dagaz|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{proto|ine-pro|dʰegʰ-|to burn}}. It is not related to Latin {{term|dies|lang=la}} (which is from [[Proto-Indo-European]] base {{proto|ine-pro|dyeu-|to shine|title=}}), but rather to {{etyl|sa}} {{term|sc=Deva|दाह|tr=dāha||heat|lang=sa}}, which came from {{proto|ine-pro|dʰegʰ-|to burn|sc=unicode}}.
* Thus, '''''today''''' and '''''day''''' are not related to {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|dies|diēs|lang=la}}, but instead to {{term|fever|lang=en}}.

